# Go proxy pattern (outbound HTTP)

## Rule
All outbound HTTP calls in Go services go through a typed subclass of `BaseProxy`. Never call `http.Client.Do` directly from a handler or a service.

## Why
`BaseProxy` centralizes auth header injection (`fbratesgoapikey`, bearer JWT), retry / timeout defaults, structured logging with `correlationId`, and error-envelope translation. Bypassing it scatters those concerns.

## Constraints
- One proxy type per downstream service (`RatesProxy`, `IQSProxy`, `AdminProxy`, etc.).
- The proxy owns URL templating, header injection, and error mapping.
- Proxy methods return typed responses or a typed error; no raw `*http.Response`.
- Context propagation is mandatory (ctx first parameter); timeouts come from the context, not from the method signature.
- Tests for the proxy use `httptest.Server`; tests for services use a proxy interface mock.

## Examples

### Good
```go
type RatesProxy struct{ *proxy.BaseProxy }

func (p *RatesProxy) Search(ctx context.Context, req SearchRequest) (*SearchResponse, error) {
    var out SearchResponse
    err := p.POST(ctx, "/v1/search", req, &out)
    return &out, err
}
```

### Bad
```go
// Ad-hoc http.Client in a service method
resp, _ := http.Post("https://rates/v1/search", "application/json", body)
```

